<i>inside me for nine months,</i>

01:59.081 --> 02:03.176
<i>someone I nursed and bathed</i>
<i>and held and sang lullabies to.</i>

02:05.007 --> 02:06.629
I have two other children, Sister,

02:06.749 --> 02:08.901
both of them perfectly normal.

02:08.970 --> 02:12.133
She sounds like quite a handful,
Mrs. Reynolds,

02:12.201 --> 02:14.599
<i>but we do not have</i>
<i>a children's ward here.</i>

02:14.667 --> 02:16.564
<i>Oh, but she's
more than a child, Sister.</i>

02:16.632 --> 02:18.727
In fact, that's the problem.

02:18.795 --> 02:20.127
She's always seemed like an adult.

02:20.194 --> 02:21.858
Do you know that she's never cried?

02:21.926 --> 02:24.090
Not once, not even
when she was a little baby.

02:24.158 --> 02:25.490
I'm going to tell you something

02:25.557 --> 02:27.354
I haven't told anyone.

02:27.422 --> 02:28.752
<i>Jenny and her little friend, Josie,</i>

02:28.820 --> 02:30.717
<i>were playing after school.</i>

02:30.785 --> 02:33.683
<i>I had told them to go out into</i>
<i>the woods to gather leaves.</i>

02:33.749 --> 02:35.712
<i>We were gonna make a fall wreath.</i>

02:35.780 --> 02:37.944
See, Josie was the only one
who would play with Jenny,

02:38.012 --> 02:39.344
and I wanted it to go well.

02:41.343 --> 02:44.972
I tried to stop him,
but he was bigger than me,

02:45.040 --> 02:48.503
and he said he would kill me, too,

02:48.571 --> 02:50.867
if I didn't stand very
still and be quiet.

02:50.934 --> 02:55.064
He was tall, he had a
beard and a brown jacket.

02:56.696 --> 02:57.995
And they never found the bearded man

02:58.062 --> 02:59.528
with the brown coat, I take it?

02:59.595 --> 03:01.658
They searched.

03:01.725 --> 03:04.290
Two days ago, I was doing the laundry,

03:04.358 --> 03:07.422
and I found this in her pocket.

03:07.489 --> 03:09.087
I can't go to the police.

03:09.154 --> 03:11.552
Sister, I can't.
She's my daughter.

03:11.620 --> 03:13.050
Oh, Mrs. Reynolds...

03:13.118 --> 03:14.715
One of my dreams

03:14.783 --> 03:17.414
for Briarcliff has been to open

03:17.481 --> 03:19.546
a children's ward.

03:19.613 --> 03:21.411
There are so many

03:21.478 --> 03:24.442
little souls who could use our help.

03:24.510 --> 03:27.806
But we can do nothing until that time.

03:29.106 --> 03:31.004
Prayer...

03:31.071 --> 03:33.901
is your strength and your ally.

03:33.968 --> 03:35.933
Could you just meet with her?

03:36.000 --> 03:37.831
She's right downstairs
with her coloring book.

03:37.898 --> 03:40.430
Sister, just help me understand,

03:40.498 --> 03:42.794
where does this evil come from?

03:42.861 --> 03:45.226
Could she have been born that way?

04:21.228 --> 04:22.659
Is there
anything more heavenly

04:22.727 --> 04:24.326
than waking from a nap

04:24.393 --> 04:25.657
to the smell of
croque-monsieur?

04:30.423 --> 04:32.387
I bet this is what your mother made you

04:32.454 --> 04:33.784
after school on a rainy day.

04:40.148 --> 04:43.777
You can scream all you want.
No one will hear you.

04:43.845 --> 04:47.408
Obviously, the basement is soundproof.

04:47.476 --> 04:49.140
Believe me, girls with
bigger sets of lungs

04:49.208 --> 04:50.571
than yours have tried before.

04:54.270 --> 04:56.067
Where's Wendy?

04:58.467 --> 05:00.563
What did you do with her body?

05:00.630 --> 05:03.528
I put her somewhere where
she'll never be found.

05:03.596 --> 05:05.596
It wouldn't do to have her body pop up

05:05.664 --> 05:07.298
now that Kit Walker has confessed

05:07.366 --> 05:10.397
to all those horrendous murders.

05:12.895 --> 05:14.659
Can I tell you a secret?

05:16.525 --> 05:19.956
Nutmeg makes all the difference

05:20.024 --> 05:22.056
in the world.

05:30.950 --> 05:32.349
Croque-monsieur
and tomato soup.

05:35.779 --> 05:38.446
The perfect mommy snack.

05:38.514 --> 05:40.083
Only I didn't have

05:40.151 --> 05:42.124
a mother to make this for me.

05:43.494 --> 05:44.961
Well, of course,

05:45.029 --> 05:47.897
I had a mother, but I never knew her.

05:50.234 --> 05:53.837
She was about your age
when she abandoned me.

05:53.905 --> 05:56.406
You grew up in an orphanage?

05:56.474 --> 05:59.543
Yeah. In the system.

05:59.611 --> 06:02.613
Where all my basic needs were met:

06:02.681 --> 06:05.349
food, water,

06:05.417 --> 06:07.318
a rudimentary education.

06:07.386 --> 06:08.486
And with the help

06:08.553 --> 06:09.987
of a leather crop,

06:10.055 --> 06:13.190
learning the difference
between right and wrong.

06:13.257 --> 06:14.624
They followed all the rules.

06:14.692 --> 06:16.326
Especially the rules against affection

06:16.394 --> 06:19.963
or any unnecessary bodily contact,

06:20.031 --> 06:24.935
because touch would certainly
spoil the child.

06:29.340 --> 06:30.607
This is good.

06:30.675 --> 06:31.842
You're right.

06:33.178 --> 06:35.679
This is good.

06:35.747 --> 06:36.714
It's delicious.

06:38.250 --> 06:41.786
I'm not trying to patronize you, Oliver.

06:41.853 --> 06:44.555
I just want you to know

06:44.623 --> 06:47.692
how much I appreciate
this act of kindness.

06:50.429 --> 06:53.765
I know what it's like to be abandoned.

06:53.832 --> 06:56.635
That's how I felt at Briarcliff.

07:09.343 --> 07:10.944
I was right about you.

07:12.914 --> 07:14.982
You're the one.

07:24.858 --> 07:29.260
Lana, I've always
been self-aware.

07:29.328 --> 07:31.129
I knew I was different
from the other kids.

07:31.197 --> 07:32.931
I was smarter.

07:32.999 --> 07:36.201
But I was also more afflicted.

07:36.269 --> 07:39.538
It's what led me to study psychiatry...

07:39.605 --> 07:41.873
to better understand my disorder.

07:41.941 --> 07:43.708
It wasn't until medical school

07:43.776 --> 07:45.911
<i>that I had</i>
<i>my first breakthrough, though.</i>

07:47.881 --> 07:49.715
Hey, Thredson, from what I hear,

07:49.783 --> 07:51.951
this is the closest you'll get
to a girlfriend this quarter.

07:53.920 --> 07:57.357
<i>I would laugh along</i>
<i>with my idiot colleagues,</i>

07:57.424 --> 08:00.860
<i>but I knew the woman on the</i>
<i>table wasn't my girlfriend.</i>

08:00.928 --> 08:02.796
I trust you gentlemen
have reviewed the material

08:02.864 --> 08:04.531
in preparation for today.

08:04.598 --> 08:07.567
<i>She was my mother.</i>
<i>She was 33 years old,</i>

08:07.635 --> 08:10.203
<i>the same age as my mother</i>
<i>when she abandoned me.</i>

08:15.710 --> 08:18.446
The same age as you, Lana.

08:25.287 --> 08:29.061
<i>Now, I knew logically, rationally,</i>

08:29.181 --> 08:30.824
<i>that the woman on the table</i>
<i>wasn't my mother.</i>

08:30.892 --> 08:34.828
<i>But somehow, in the</i>
<i>cosmic joke that is my life,</i>

08:34.895 --> 08:37.063
<i>I felt like she could be.</i>

08:39.301 --> 08:42.669
<i>And it was poetic justice</i>
<i>that I would be meeting her</i>

08:42.736 --> 08:45.706
<i>for the first time on a slab</i>
<i>in my gross anatomy class.</i>

09:00.256 --> 09:04.226
<i>It was then that I knew</i>
<i>what I was missing.</i>

09:06.930 --> 09:08.624
A mother's touch.

09:10.667 --> 09:12.874
Skin-to-skin contact.

09:20.410 --> 09:22.945
<i>It's what I was craving.</i>

09:23.013 --> 09:27.017
<i>It's what I was missing my whole life.</i>

09:29.788 --> 09:33.725
<i>Oh, but she smelled of formaldehyde.</i>

09:39.998 --> 09:45.802
And her skin, even after I
removed it, was cold and stiff.

09:45.870 --> 09:48.772
Have you ever read

09:48.840 --> 09:51.075
or heard about the Harlow studies?

09:52.277 --> 09:53.777
Baby rhesus monkeys

09:53.845 --> 09:55.746
were separated
from their mothers after birth,

09:55.814 --> 09:58.483
and they were given
two substitute mothers:

09:58.550 --> 10:01.052
a wire mesh one with milk

10:01.119 --> 10:05.022
and the other covered in terrycloth.

10:05.090 --> 10:09.360
<i>Every</i> monkey preferred
the terrycloth-covered mother,

10:09.428 --> 10:11.529
even if it didn't have milk.

10:11.597 --> 10:13.731
Because of the warmth?

10:13.799 --> 10:14.932
Because of the skin.

10:17.836 --> 10:20.237
Even monkeys know the difference.

10:24.676 --> 10:28.011
I tried, I really tried.

10:32.782 --> 10:36.250
But that cadaver did nothing
to quiet my craving.

10:36.317 --> 10:38.251
I needed someone...

10:41.121 --> 10:43.189
...a little more lively.

11:12.888 --> 11:14.522
Warm living skin.

11:16.625 --> 11:18.627
No, no, no, no, no.

11:18.695 --> 11:20.763
It's okay.

11:20.831 --> 11:22.899
It's okay, because now that you're here,

11:22.966 --> 11:25.868
all of that work is behind me.

11:28.906 --> 11:30.741
Mommy.

11:37.315 --> 11:39.383
Hello?

11:39.451 --> 11:40.783
Sister Jude.

11:40.851 --> 11:43.016
It's Sam Goodman.

11:43.083 --> 11:44.816
Sam, I tried calling you,

11:44.884 --> 11:46.451
but you never got back to me.

11:46.519 --> 11:48.686
I was working on your case.

11:48.754 --> 11:51.956
Yes, but I-I-I asked you
to stop.

11:52.024 --> 11:53.257
I mean, this girl, this mental patient,

11:53.325 --> 11:54.859
she wasn't Anne Frank.

11:54.926 --> 11:58.095
I mean, she just made
the whole thing up.

11:58.162 --> 11:59.529
Well, somehow,

11:59.597 --> 12:00.997
she got it right.

12:01.065 --> 12:02.465
He is Hans Grouper.

12:02.533 --> 12:04.801
He was an SS officer and a physician...

12:04.868 --> 12:07.437
at Auschwitz.
What?

12:07.504 --> 12:10.173
Did you say...

12:10.241 --> 12:11.441
she got it right?

12:11.509 --> 12:12.642
After the liberation,

12:12.710 --> 12:14.943
he obtained a laissez-passer

12:15.011 --> 12:19.713
from the International Red Cross
under the name Arthur Arden.

12:21.349 --> 12:24.852
I have the original documents

12:24.919 --> 12:27.354
from the Red Cross,

12:27.422 --> 12:31.425
but I need Grouper's fingerprint
to establish a match.

12:31.492 --> 12:34.427
Be careful. The man is dangerous
and a flight risk.

12:35.996 --> 12:38.131
These men are always on their guard.

12:38.198 --> 12:40.032
The moment they get nervous,
they disappear.

12:40.100 --> 12:42.368
As soon as you have the print,

12:42.435 --> 12:45.704
bring it directly to the motel.

12:52.410 --> 12:54.143
Who are you?

12:54.211 --> 12:55.278
I'm Jenny.

12:56.580 --> 12:58.914
I told your mother,

12:58.982 --> 13:01.116
we don't have a children's ward here.

13:01.184 --> 13:02.484
Where is she?
She's gone.

13:02.552 --> 13:04.986
She kissed me on the cheek

13:05.054 --> 13:07.955
and said, "Be good, Jenny."

13:15.230 --> 13:16.863
Sister Mary Eunice!

13:16.931 --> 13:19.565
I need help here.

13:23.207 --> 13:24.640
Monsignor, thank you for coming.

13:24.708 --> 13:26.175
Oh, it's my pleasure.

13:26.243 --> 13:28.444
I consider it a privilege
to perform last rites.

13:28.512 --> 13:30.445
Oh, thank God you're
a man of compassion.

13:30.513 --> 13:32.113
We called several priests in the area,

13:32.180 --> 13:35.048
but they were all in a panic
over the news reports.

13:35.116 --> 13:38.385
Especially after they published
those grim pictures of her.

13:38.453 --> 13:39.853
What exactly is wrong with her?

13:39.921 --> 13:41.354
No one knows.

13:41.422 --> 13:44.357
Our doctors have ordered
a battery of tests.

13:44.425 --> 13:46.326
But she did test positive for TB.

13:46.393 --> 13:49.162
Oh, I didn't realize
there were still new cases.

13:49.230 --> 13:51.297
I should warn you...

13:51.365 --> 13:53.533
the sight of her is quite shocking.

13:55.268 --> 13:57.036
We're all God's creatures.

14:04.579 --> 14:06.981
I'll be in the hall if you need me.

14:09.684 --> 14:11.519
Hi, child.

14:28.104 --> 14:29.304
Shelly?

14:40.917 --> 14:43.667
Oh, look at that,

14:43.787 --> 14:44.772
Father James.

14:44.888 --> 14:47.023
This will make a splendid dayroom

14:47.090 --> 14:48.291
for our residents.

14:48.358 --> 14:51.060
All right, I thought all

14:51.128 --> 14:53.429
TB patients had been cleared out.

14:53.496 --> 14:54.997
These are
the incurables,

14:55.064 --> 14:57.366
those whose tuberculosis
was too far advanced

14:57.434 --> 14:58.834
for any of the new miracle drugs

14:58.902 --> 15:01.370
to have an effect.
God bless.

15:01.438 --> 15:05.174
Well, he hasn't yet.

15:05.242 --> 15:07.476
Dr. Arthur Arden,
Briarcliff's

15:07.544 --> 15:10.146
Tubercular Ward's supervising physician.

15:10.214 --> 15:12.649
Former supervising
physician, I should say.

15:12.716 --> 15:14.985
Father Timothy Howard...

15:15.052 --> 15:16.520
Yes, I know who you are.

15:16.587 --> 15:17.621
You're the new owner.

15:19.057 --> 15:20.991
Sally Starns.

15:21.058 --> 15:23.393
She was actually a
nurse here at one time.

15:23.461 --> 15:26.863
She won't live till morning,
not if she's lucky.

15:26.931 --> 15:28.464
Through this holy anointing,

15:28.532 --> 15:29.766
may the Lord and his love

15:29.834 --> 15:31.267
and mercy help you with the grace

15:31.335 --> 15:32.535
of the Holy Spirit.

15:34.272 --> 15:36.573
May the Lord who frees you from sin

15:36.641 --> 15:38.809
save you and raise you up.

15:38.877 --> 15:40.444
It's all right, my daughter.

15:40.512 --> 15:41.945
The Prince of Peace

15:42.013 --> 15:44.182
opens his arms to you.

15:48.488 --> 15:50.456
Back when the epidemic was at its worst,

15:50.524 --> 15:52.124
we'd sometimes move more than

15:52.192 --> 15:54.393
100 bodies a week down through here.
Oh.

15:54.461 --> 15:57.663
- How did you manage to keep up with
all the burials? - There were no burials.

15:57.731 --> 16:00.966
Most of the people here
have long since been forgotten.

16:01.034 --> 16:02.902
We incinerate the bodies

16:02.969 --> 16:05.371
in the crematorium out back

16:05.439 --> 16:07.640
and store the ashes in here.

16:07.708 --> 16:10.275
All these wasted lives.

16:10.343 --> 16:12.644
All these wasted opportunities.

16:12.712 --> 16:14.179
I suppose it will be a relief for you

16:14.247 --> 16:15.748
to finally leave this place.

16:15.815 --> 16:17.483
The end of my
tenure at Briarcliff

16:17.550 --> 16:19.485
also means the end of my research.

16:19.552 --> 16:21.520
Research?

16:21.588 --> 16:24.889
I've been working
on an immune booster.

16:24.957 --> 16:28.293
It's a sort of bacterial
cocktail, if you will.

16:28.360 --> 16:29.961
It would actually inhibit most disease

16:30.029 --> 16:32.297
from ever taking hold in the human body.

16:32.365 --> 16:34.566
What would you need
to further your work?

16:34.634 --> 16:36.636
Human trials would have
been the next step.

16:36.704 --> 16:39.372
I assume it would be difficult
to find volunteers.

16:39.440 --> 16:41.207
From the general public, yes.

16:41.275 --> 16:44.244
But there are those whose lives
otherwise serve no purpose.

16:44.311 --> 16:45.946
Through our work together,
they would have contributed

16:46.014 --> 16:47.214
to the greater good.

16:48.750 --> 16:51.953
A good that would not go unnoticed.

16:52.020 --> 16:54.121
Even in Rome.

17:25.520 --> 17:26.650
I'm sorry.

17:26.717 --> 17:28.584
Would you have preferred Mozart?

17:28.652 --> 17:30.286
Jude was right about you.

17:30.354 --> 17:31.253
You're a monster.

17:33.022 --> 17:34.889
Why do you look for the speck

17:34.957 --> 17:37.325
of sawdust in your brother's eye...

17:37.392 --> 17:40.560
and pay no attention
to the plank in your own?

17:40.628 --> 17:43.997
I saw that girl, what you did

17:44.064 --> 17:45.298
to Shelly.

17:45.365 --> 17:47.566
All in the name of progress.

17:47.634 --> 17:49.167
Isn't that what we agreed upon?

17:49.235 --> 17:51.602
No, you told me this
was for the greater good.

17:51.670 --> 17:53.104
You mutilated her!

17:53.171 --> 17:55.038
Perhaps.

17:55.106 --> 17:57.006
But you're missing the entire point.

17:58.375 --> 18:00.709
Briarcliff is a receptacle

18:00.777 --> 18:02.177
for human waste.

18:02.245 --> 18:04.813
Each patient a perfect example

18:04.881 --> 18:07.382
of an evolutionary failure.

18:12.755 --> 18:14.189
